that got left out,

00:36:31.420 --> 00:36:34.240
are you going to have a
director's cut or something?

00:36:34.240 --> 00:36:35.849
Can I buy the extended Blu-ray?

00:36:35.849 --> 00:36:37.640
MARK STUART DAY: One
way I think about that

00:36:37.640 --> 00:36:44.960
is to say that I have the
material for a sequel,

00:36:44.960 --> 00:36:50.220
or I have material
for smaller packages.

00:36:50.220 --> 00:36:52.730
Some of the stuff that
wound up getting cut

00:36:52.730 --> 00:36:55.430
probably would work well as
essential knowledge books.

00:36:55.430 --> 00:36:59.762
So that's another possibility.

00:36:59.762 --> 00:37:00.680
Yeah?

00:37:00.680 --> 00:37:04.970
AUDIENCE: You have a website
listed on one of those pages.

00:37:04.970 --> 00:37:09.450
Do you think about putting them
as blog posts on the website?

00:37:09.450 --> 00:37:12.020
MARK STUART DAY: You mean the
things that I had to cut out?

00:37:12.020 --> 00:37:12.450
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:37:12.450 --> 00:37:13.324
MARK STUART DAY: Yes.

00:37:13.324 --> 00:37:16.760
No, I think that that is
another likely destination.

00:37:16.760 --> 00:37:20.390
I have a lot of
material, not just

00:37:20.390 --> 00:37:23.120
because of what I cut out of
the book, but because I do still

00:37:23.120 --> 00:37:24.500
have this writing routine.

00:37:24.500 --> 00:37:28.430
And so pretty much
every day, I'm

00:37:28.430 --> 00:37:32.820
writing whatever things
cross my fool mind that day.

00:37:32.820 --> 00:37:35.450
And so some of the
time that's technical.

00:37:35.450 --> 00:37:37.160
And some of the time it isn't.

00:37:37.160 --> 00:37:39.950
But it does mean that
there is a lot of stuff

00:37:39.950 --> 00:37:43.410
for blog posts and
possibly future books.

00:37:43.410 --> 00:37:44.390
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:37:44.390 --> 00:37:46.490
So I just want to ask,
throughout the process

00:37:46.490 --> 00:37:49.534
of writing the book and getting
the book published, which part

00:37:49.534 --> 00:37:50.700
do you think is the hardest?

00:37:50.700 --> 00:37:52.610
Like, what's your
biggest challenge?

00:37:52.610 --> 00:37:56.864
And which part is the most
fun or the most enjoyable?

00:37:56.864 --> 00:37:59.030
MARK STUART DAY: The writing
itself, especially when

00:37:59.030 --> 00:38:02.670
the writing is going
well, is a lot of fun,

00:38:02.670 --> 00:38:04.190
and especially when
you're convinced

00:38:04.190 --> 00:38:06.777
that the fact that
you're writing well

00:38:06.777 --> 00:38:08.360
and that it feels
good means that it's

00:38:08.360 --> 00:38:12.800
going to turn effortlessly
into some fabulous book.

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:14.960
I think that the
parts that are hard--

00:38:19.490 --> 00:38:23.150
cutting the stuff that you've
written so as to get down

00:38:23.150 --> 00:38:26.870
to a word count
turns out to be hard,

00:38:26.870 --> 00:38:30.740
if you're going to
get it to be coherent.

00:38:30.740 --> 00:38:34.910
Doing the index
was simultaneously

00:38:34.910 --> 00:38:37.850
fascinating and excruciating.

00:38:37.850 --> 00:38:40.190
It's a fascinating
process because you're

00:38:40.190 --> 00:38:43.550
working with the final
text of your book.

00:38:43.550 --> 00:38:46.490
And what you're trying
to do is to collect

00:38:46.490 --> 00:38:49.700
all of the conceptually
related things, wherever

00:38:49.700 --> 00:38:52.010
they are scattered in the book.

00:38:52.010 --> 00:38:53.900
And what you
discover is it's kind

00:38:53.900 --> 00:38:55.970
of like an X-ray of your book.

00:38:55.970 --> 00:38:58.702
You wind up realizing, oh, I
talked about this thing there,

00:38:58.702 --> 00:39:00.910
and I also talked about it
here, but unfortunately, I

00:39:00.910 --> 00:39:04.000
used different words
in the two places.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:06.620
And so you learn a lot
about the way you write.

00:39:06.620 --> 00:39:10.490
But it's unfortunately too late
for you to do anything about it

00:39:10.490 --> 00:39:12.470
because you're doing it
on the final version.

00:39:12.470 --> 00:39:16.130
And they're very clear
with you that you do not

00:39:16.130 --> 00:39:19.140
get to rewrite your
book at this phase.

00:39:19.140 --> 00:39:24.124
So that also-- my wife will
tell you that the period of time

00:39:24.124 --> 00:39:25.790
when I was doing the
index, I would just

00:39:25.790 --> 00:39:28.860
keep coming down and
saying, oh, I'm almost done,

00:39:28.860 --> 00:39:29.660
I'm almost done.

00:39:29.660 --> 00:39:31.290
I would do that for
weeks at a time.

00:39:31.290 --> 00:39:33.737
[LAUGHING]

00:39:33.737 --> 00:39:35.945
AUDIENCE: So you have two
interesting ranges in there

00:39:35.945 --> 00:39:37.922
of how long it took
you to write the book.

00:39:37.922 --> 00:39:39.380
But something you
didn't mention is

00:39:39.380 --> 00:39:41.300
how long it took you to
acquire the knowledge

00:39:41.300 --> 00:39:42.100
to write the book.

00:39:42.100 --> 00:39:44.100
And that's from
the very beginning

00:39:44.100 --> 00:39:46.070
up until the ending, how
much time you invested

00:39:46.070 --> 00:39:48.236
during the writing to acquire
the knowledge that you

00:39:48.236 --> 00:39:49.910
lacked when you started.

00:39:49.910 --> 00:39:52.890
MARK STUART DAY: So
that's a good question.

00:39:52.890 --> 00:39:54.830
One way we could
talk about this is

00:39:54.830 --> 00:39:58.310
to say that the things
that I was writing about

00:39:58.310 --> 00:40:01.040
are things that I
have effectively

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:05.250
learned over 30-plus years.

00:40:05.250 --> 00:40:07.070
On the other hand,
there were also

00:40:07.070 --> 00:40:11.450
some things where I
needed to go and learn

00:40:11.450 --> 00:40:15.950
a specific piece of
technology just for the book.

00:40:15.950 --> 00:40:20.030
Now, one example of this
was that I didn't really

00:40:20.030 --> 00:40:23.380
understand some details
of how Wi-Fi works.

00:40:23.380 --> 00:40:25.910
And I thought, that seems
like it would be a good thing

00:40:25.910 --> 00:40:26.600
to include.

00:40:26.600 --> 00:40:30.530
Now it turns out that that wound
up on the cutting room floor

00:40:30.530 --> 00:40:32.180
when I had to cut
the book down again.

00:40:32.180 --> 00:40:35.810
So it was a case where
I learned something

00:40:35.810 --> 00:40:37.280
in a kind of a tactical mode.

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:39.770
And I produced an explanation
of it that I liked,

00:40:39.770 --> 00:40:41.720
and then I had to
throw it away again.

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:43.700
But most of it, I
think, came down

00:40:43.700 --> 00:40:50.060
to I had learned a
lot of this stuff

00:40:50.060 --> 00:40:52.670
across the different
kinds of things I've done

00:40:52.670 --> 00:40:54.860
in industry and in academia.

00:40:54.860 --> 00:40:58.200
And really, the main
work of writing it,

00:40:58.200 --> 00:41:01.010
other than the
construction of the text,

00:41:01.010 --> 00:41:04.070
was to be thinking about
those things and saying,

00:41:04.070 --> 00:41:08.600
I know how I would explain
those to a technical person,

00:41:08.600 --> 00:41:10.820
but I have to think
about it differently.

00:41:10.820 --> 00:41:13.532
I can't just fall back
on those kinds of things.

00:41:13.532 --> 00:41:14.990
I'm going to have
to find some kind

00:41:14.990 --> 00:41:18.290
of a metaphor, some kind of
an example, some kind of way

00:41:18.290 --> 00:41:19.700
of tackling it.

00:41:19.700 --> 00:41:23.270
And so I think that was a lot
of the intellectual process

00:41:23.270 --> 00:41:27.440
of doing the book, was kind
of finding ways of saying,

00:41:27.440 --> 00:41:29.480
I've got something
interesting technical to say,

00:41:29.480 --> 00:41:34.140
but I can't use the ways that
people typically talk about it.

00:41:34.140 --> 00:41:38.180
AUDIENCE: So what did you
leave out, other than Wi-Fi?

00:41:38.180 --> 00:41:39.950
MARK STUART DAY:
Atomic transactions

00:41:39.950 --> 00:41:41.600
I had to leave out pretty--

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:43.670
there's a mention
of them, but it's

00:41:43.670 --> 00:41:45.530
sort of a hand-wave
that says, they

00:41:45.530 --> 00:41:48.440
solve all kinds of problems.

00:41:48.440 --> 00:41:51.710
I had to leave out
synchronizer failure--

00:41:51.710 --> 00:41:54.740
the sort of boundary between the
analog and the digital world,

00:41:54.740 --> 00:41:56.150
even though there are
some fascinating things

00:41:56.150 --> 00:41:56.900
that happen there.

00:42:01.380 --> 00:42:04.460
I have lots of slightly
dubious musings

00:42:04.460 --> 00:42:07.080
about the nature of time.

00:42:07.080 --> 00:42:11.247
And so those all
wound up on the floor.

00:42:11.247 --> 00:42:13.580
I think that atomic transaction
was probably the biggest

00:42:13.580 --> 00:42:16.220
piece that I had to take out.

00:42:16.220 --> 00:42:19.040
AUDIENCE: So were you
worried that calling

00:42:19.040 --> 00:42:23.780
the book "Bits to Bitcoin"
would lead people to focus more

00:42:23.780 --> 00:42:25.605
on the Bitcoin than the bits?

00:42:25.605 --> 00:42:26.480
MARK STUART DAY: Yes.

00:42:26.480 --> 00:42:29.720
Well, that's still an
ongoing challenge for me,

00:42:29.720 --> 00:42:32.210
in terms of the marketing.

00:42:32.210 --> 00:42:36.050
On the one hand, it's nice
to have a title that attracts

00:42:36.050 --> 00:42:37.820
attention, because it's timely.

00:42:37.820 --> 00:42:39.770
On the other hand,
there is a little bit

00:42:39.770 --> 00:42:44.960
of the possibility of either
disappointing the reader

00:42:44.960 --> 00:42:51.960
because they expect it to be all
about Bitcoin or of misleading

00:42:51.960 --> 00:42:53.060
the reader that they--

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:59.770
so yeah, the title is
sometimes a bit of a challenge.

00:42:59.770 --> 00:43:02.470
But as you can see
from those other ones,

00:43:02.470 --> 00:43:05.620
like "Unstoppable Time
Traveling Phantoms" or "Machines

00:43:05.620 --> 00:43:08.127
Behind the Curtain,"
it's much improved.

00:43:08.127 --> 00:43:10.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:10.350 --> 00:43:11.520
AUDIENCE: Thank the speaker.

00:43:11.520 --> 00:43:11.820
MARK STUART DAY: Great.

00:43:11.820 --> 00:43:12.420
Thank you all.

00:43:12.420 --> 00:43:15.770
[APPLAUSE]

